Here's a possible JSON object representing an inventory low event generated by the CloudEvents specification (version 1.0):

```json
{
    "specversion": "1.0",
    "id": "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001",
    "source": "https://example.com/inventory-low-event",
    "type": "com.example.inventory.low",
    "subject": "inventory-low-event",
    "time": "2021-09-20T11:00:00.000Z",
    "datacontenttype": "application/json",
    "data": {
        "items": [
            {
                "id": "item-id-1",
                "quantity": 2
            },
            {
                "id": "item-id-2",
                "quantity": 5
            },
            {
                "id": "item-id-3",
                "quantity": 1
            }
        ],
        "total": 7
    }
}
```

The `specversion` field contains the version number of the CloudEvents specification (1.0). The `id` field is required and can be any unique identifier for the event. The `source` field identifies the source of the event. The `type` field specifies the type of the event. The `subject` field identifies the subject of the event. The `time` field contains the time of the event. The `datacontenttype` field specifies the content type of the data in the event. The `data` field contains the data of the event. The `items` and `total` fields contain the items and the total of items in the inventory respectively. The nested `data` field contains the items as nested objects with `id`, `quantity`, and `total` fields.

